# Guide: How to Push Files to GitHub using Git LFS

# 1. Clone your GitHub repository
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/<your-repo-name>.git

# 2. Go inside the project folder in the system
cd <your-repo-name>/

# code for find large files in a folder 
find . -type f -size +90M

# 3. Track large files with Git LFS (for example: .h5 and .keras model files)
git lfs track "*.h5"
git lfs track "*.keras"

# 4. Add the Git LFS tracking config file
git add .gitattributes

# 5. Add all files (code, datasets, models, etc.)
git add .

# 6. Commit with a clear message
git commit -m "Add project files and track large model files using Git LFS"

# 7. Push to GitHub
git push origin main

# Notes:
# - GitHub has a 100MB file size limit for normal Git.
# - Git LFS should be used for large files (models, datasets, etc.).
# - If you modify the last commit (e.g., with git commit --amend), use:
#   git push origin main --force

